d why the killings ended. This deeply researched book is a comprehensive and chilling history of an American genocide. Madley describes pre-contact California and precursors to the genocide before explaining how the Gold Rush stirred vigilante violence against California Indians. He narrates the rise of a state-sanctioned killing machine and the broad societal, judicial, and political support for genocide. Many participated: vigilantes, volunteer state militiamen, U.S. Army soldiers, U.S. congressmen, California governors, and others. The state and federal governments spent at least $1,700,000 on campaigns against California Indians. Besides evaluating government officials’ culpability, Madley considers why the slaughter constituted genocide and how other possible genocides within and beyond the Americas might be investigated using the methods presented in this groundbreaking book.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mrz 2022) 0aGenocidezCaliforniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCrimes againstzCaliforniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aIndians of North AmericaxCrimes againstzCalifornia. 0aIndians of North AmericaxViolence againstzCaliforniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aIndians of North AmericazCaliforniaxGovernment relations. 0aIndians of North AmericazCaliforniaxHistoryy19th century. 0aIndians of North AmericazCalifornia. 0aIndians, Treatment ofzCalifornia. 0aState-sponsored terrorismzCalifornia. 7aHISTORY / Native American.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z978311066771440uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030018217040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300182170423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300182170/original  a978-3-11-066771-4  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016